Are there any plans, or is it even possible, to support NativeLibrary in dotnet standard?

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.runtime.interopservices.nativelibrary?view=netcore-3.1

I have a dotnet standard 2.1 library that needs to load a c++ library, but we want to support multiple versions of the library (linux and windows).

Example usage: 
```C#
static class NativeMethods
{
	private const string LibraryName = "something";
	static NativeMethods()
	{
		NativeLibrary.SetDllImportResolver(typeof(NativeMethods).Assembly, ImportResolver);
	}
	private static IntPtr ImportResolver(string libraryName, Assembly assembly, DllImportSearchPath? searchPath)
	{
		IntPtr libHandle = IntPtr.Zero;
		if (libraryName == NativeMethods.LibraryName)
		{
			string library;
			if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.Linux))
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.so";	
			} 
			else if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.dylib";
			}
			else
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.dll";
			}
			var libraryLoaded = NativeLibrary.TryLoad(library, assembly, DllImportSearchPath.AssemblyDirectory, out libHandle);
			if (!libraryLoaded)
			{
				throw new Exception($"Unable to Load Library: {library}");
			}
		}
		return libHandle;
	}
```

Alternatively, is there another way to load a cross platform C++ code in a dotnet standard?

**Version Used**: 
Repros on SharpLab on the latest commit to `main` (bc98ed9) as well as Visual Studio Enterprise 16.9.4.
**Steps to Reproduce**:
Compile the following:
```csharp
#nullable enable
using System;
static double Sum(double? a, double? b)
{
    if (a.HasValue != b.HasValue)
    {
        throw new ArgumentException("Both must be null or non-null together.");
    }

    return a.HasValue
        ? a.Value + b.Value
        : double.NaN;
}
```
SharpLab snippet: https://sharplab.io/#v2:EYLgtghglgdgPgYhgVwDaosVBTABNmTHAWACgABAJgEYzzqA2XAEwHtks8BlZMACjYccAflwQANC3adRwAJRkA3mVyrcUAGa4+EAHQAJCAGcAahFTI8AQgC8uYAeNmL2BaTW5l7j2oAuACwAnVgB3XBhsMIBBQIBzXgJfAFEADwBjbAAHXyhWGD4AIgAhVgDcMGQjX3s8FHRcVkDwvIBaOtRcX1ZY7ADsQN0CuQBuFTUAXzIx1XIAdjFHU3NLaZ9RPWdLXABqe11N7FWPECkhbF0AOQgL0dJxoA=

**Expected Behavior**:
No nullability warnings

**Actual Behavior**:
CS8629: Nullable value type may be null.

Specifically, it warns that `b.Value` is not safe, even though it provably is:
1. `b.HasValue` is equal to `a.HasValue`
1. `a.HasValue` is `true`
1. Therefore, `b.HasValue` is `true`
1. Therefore, `b.Value` is safe

**Workarounds**:
Of course, I can always just suppress, change it to `.GetValueOrDefault()`, or rewrite it so that the two conditions are combined, to something like:
```csharp
#nullable enable
using System;
static double Sum(double? a, double? b)
{
    if (a.HasValue)
    {
        if (!b.HasValue)
        {
            throw new ArgumentException("Both must be null or non-null together.");
        }

        return a.Value + b.Value;
    }
    else if (b.HasValue)
    {
        throw new ArgumentException("Both must be null or non-null together.");
    }
    else
    {
        return double.NaN;
    }
}
```

What I want to avoid is something like this, however, as it adds a branch that I don't think can be covered (so code coverage looks worse):
```csharp
#nullable enable
using System;
static double Sum(double? a, double? b)
{
    if (a.HasValue != b.HasValue)
    {
        throw new ArgumentException("Both must be null or non-null together.");
    }

    return a.HasValue && b.HasValue
        ? a.Value + b.Value
        : double.NaN;
}
```

And changing `&&` to `&` is a bit too esoteric.

- Add `NewLineOption.PropertyPatternClauses` to represent `* is {` pattern
Is this a good name? I followed what it's called in the node. After this gets merged I'll also update the [docs here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/fundamentals/code-analysis/style-rules/formatting-rules#csharp_new_line_before_open_brace) to reflect this new value.
- Adhere to the "new line before open brace" formatting rule for `is` pattern matching

Example:

```editorconfig
[*.cs]
csharp_new_line_before_open_brace = none
```

```cs
public class TestInner {
    public string Name { get; }
}

public class Test {
    public string Name { get; }
    public TestInner Inner { get; }
}

public class Program {
    public bool IsAbc(Test test) {
        return test is { // Here
            Name: "foo",
            Inner: { // Here
                Name: "bar"
            }
        };
    }
}
```

Before this change, the lines noted above would report IDE0055 and the suggested code fix converts to using a new line (violating our config). After this change, the formatting rule is now respected in `is` pattern matching clauses, just like in all other places.

